`crates/steno/tests` is the integration-test surface for the `steno` crate's whole compilation pipeline — parsing, count/type expansion, rendering (plain/smart/snippet/struct), stroke encoding, and the nvim plugin consuming the generated snippets. Depending on this subtree buys confidence that the pipeline's stages compose correctly end-to-end and that the shipped `dict.steno` corpus is internally consistent (no duplicate strokes, canonical key order, zero dictionary-build collisions, no non-terminal masquerading as terminal); it is not where unit-level parser/renderer behavior is pinned in isolation from real data (most files exercise both a synthetic fixture *and* the corpus).

The dominant coupling across files is a shared dependency on one real file, `dict.steno` at the repo root, read via `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR/../../dict.steno` (or `include_str!` with an equivalent relative path) in at least ten of these files. Any edit to that corpus — renaming/removing a stroke, changing a count/arity/flag, adding an `@literal` block — can silently break tests across `blocks.rs`, `expand.rs`, `expand_types.rs`, `parse_source.rs`, `render.rs`, `smart.rs`, `snippet.rs`, and `stroke_order.rs` simultaneously, since each hardcodes specific stroke strings or aggregate counts (entry totals, chunk counts, dictionary-key counts) against current corpus contents. Two files (`smart.rs`, `snippet.rs`) additionally hand-construct a synthetic `TypedEntry` (`` `${%0}` `` template) via `parse_template` + manual `Entry`/`EntryFlags` because the corpus stroke they originally targeted (`STKWR-LT`) was repurposed to a `let` binding — anyone changing `TypedEntry`'s field set must update both `terminal_entry`/`template_literal` helpers in lockstep or these synthesized paths silently diverge from real `expand_dict` output.

The pipeline order matters and is exercised in stages: `parse_source.rs`/`parse_template.rs` cover the parser and its exact error-message wording; `expand.rs` (Pass A, count expansion) and `expand_types.rs` (Pass B, `%t` type-slot expansion) cover the two expansion passes and their composition; `render.rs`/`smart.rs`/`blocks.rs` cover profile-specific rendering (plain vs. smart vs. struct/`@literal`); `snippet.rs` covers the final Plover-snippet/sentinel-token layer; `editor.rs` independently exercises the editor-simulation/`Behaviors` API used by `blocks.rs`'s `intended()` helper and by real users typing rendered output; `stroke.rs` and `stroke_order.rs` cover the low-level stroke encode/decode contract, with `stroke_order.rs` specifically linting that the corpus stays in the canonical key order `render_stroke` would silently normalize to. `nvim_plugin.rs` is the only file driving actual Neovim buffer state, catching bugs the Rust-only pipeline tests can't (cursor arithmetic, `vim.snippet.expand` interaction).

A cross-cutting invariant checked in multiple places: non-terminal ("family root") strokes must never be sentinel-wrapped or terminal-rendered (asserted directly in `snippet.rs`'s `no_terminal_is_a_prefix_of_another_stroke`, and implicitly relied on by `nvim_plugin.rs`'s chord-extension test and the plugin's own "only terminals sentinel-wrapped" contract).

No `intent.md` exists for this directory, so no divergence can be assessed.